      <h1>Car Insurance Guide</h1>
      <p>Your comprehensive resource to understanding car insurance, from choosing coverage types to lowering your premium and comparing quotes.</p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <p>Car insurance can be complicated, but understanding the basics ensures you're protected without overpaying. This guide breaks down everything you need to know about coverages, rates, and strategies for getting the best deal.</p>

      <h2>Liability vs. Collision vs. Comprehensive</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Liability Insurance:</strong> Required in most states. It covers bodily injury and property damage you cause to others in an accident. It does not cover your own vehicle.</li>
        <li><strong>Collision Coverage:</strong> Pays to repair or replace your vehicle if you are at fault in an accident with another vehicle or object.</li>
        <li><strong>Comprehensive Coverage:</strong> Covers damage to your car from non-collision incidents such as theft, vandalism, fire, natural disasters, or hitting an animal.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Deductible Strategies</h2>
      <p>Your deductible is the amount you pay out-of-pocket before insurance kicks in. A higher deductible (e.g., $1,000 instead of $500) will lower your monthly premium. Choose a deductible you can comfortably afford to pay in an emergency.</p>

      <h2>Factors Affecting Your Rates</h2>
      <p>Insurance companies use multiple factors to determine your rate:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Age and Gender:</strong> Young, inexperienced drivers (especially teens) pay the highest rates.</li>
        <li><strong>Credit History:</strong> In many states, a higher credit score can significantly lower your premium.</li>
        <li><strong>Location:</strong> Living in urban areas with higher rates of accidents and theft increases premiums.</li>
        <li><strong>Vehicle Type:</strong> Expensive, high-performance, or frequently stolen vehicles cost more to insure.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How to Lower Premiums</h2>
      <p>Don't overpay for coverage. Ask about discounts for safe driving, good grades (for students), military service, or installing anti-theft devices. Maintaining a clean driving record is the most reliable way to keep rates low.</p>

      <h2>Bundling Discounts</h2>
      <p>Most insurers offer substantial discounts if you bundle multiple policies, such as auto and home or renters insurance, under the same company.</p>

      <h2>Usage-Based Insurance (Telematics)</h2>
      <p>Programs like Snapshot (Progressive) or Drive Safe & Save (State Farm) track your driving habits via an app or plug-in device. Safe drivers with low mileage can see significant discounts, but poor driving habits could increase your rate.</p>

      <h2>Gap Insurance</h2>
      <p>If you total a new car, insurance only pays its current depreciated value. If you owe more on your loan or lease than the car is worth, Gap Insurance covers the "gap" so you aren't left paying for a car you no longer have.</p>

      <h2>Uninsured/Underinsured Motorist Coverage</h2>
      <p>This covers your medical bills and property damage if you are hit by a driver who has no insurance or insufficient coverage to pay for the damages.</p>

      <h2>SR-22 Explained</h2>
      <p>An SR-22 is a form your insurance company files with the state proving you carry the minimum required liability insurance. It is usually required for high-risk drivers, such as those with DUIs or multiple serious infractions.</p>

      <h2>When to Drop Collision Coverage</h2>
      <p>If the cost of your comprehensive and collision premiums plus your deductible is more than your older car's actual cash value, it might be time to drop them. As a rule of thumb, consider dropping full coverage when your car's value drops below a few thousand dollars.</p>

      <h2>How to File a Claim</h2>
      <p>After an accident, ensure everyone is safe, call the police, take photos, and exchange info. Contact your insurer as soon as possible via their app or phone to start the claim process. Provide all documentation and cooperate fully with the adjuster.</p>

      <h2>Comparing Quotes</h2>
      <p>Rates vary wildly between companies. It's recommended to shop around every 1-2 years. Consider comparing quotes from:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Progressive:</strong> Great for comparing rates and usage-based discounts.</li>
        <li><strong>GEICO:</strong> Often competitive for drivers with clean records.</li>
        <li><strong>State Farm:</strong> Excellent agent network and bundling options.</li>
        <li><strong>Allstate:</strong> Good for safe driving bonuses and comprehensive coverage.</li>
        <li><strong>USAA:</strong> Often the cheapest and best service, but restricted to military members and their families.</li>
        <li><strong>Root:</strong> App-based insurance that bases rates primarily on your driving behavior during a test drive period.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Teen Driver Insurance Tips</h2>
      <p>Insuring a teen is expensive. Keep costs down by having them take a certified driver's education course, maintaining a "B" average or higher for a good student discount, and assigning them to the oldest, safest vehicle on your policy rather than buying them a new sports car.</p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      {faqs.map(f => (
        <div>
          <h3>{f.q}</h3>
          <p>{f.a}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>

